ay need to adjust the up-force setting.";i:31;s:75:"Activate the garage door opener with the emergency release still pulled to.";i:32;s:116:"These would be to detect an obstruction when the doors is closing and has not yet reached the fully closed position.";i:33;s:228:"I suspect there is an adjustable limit switch in the motor gear box that determines when the door should stop moving downwards just before it touches the ground with a separate limit switch to stop it in the fully open position.";i:34;s:66:"Below youll find all you need to know about garage door alignment.";i:35;s:96:"Check out our ultimate garage door buyers guide for more information about garage doors as well.";i:36;s:38:"A Crooked or Off-Balanced Garage Door.";i:37;s:75:"If your door sits off balanced it wont just magically straighten itself up.";i:38;s:55:"It may be crooked or sit wonky within the door opening.";i:39;s:78:"Read on to learn how to troubleshoot a garage door thats not opening properly.";i:40;s:25:"Check the Manual Release.";i:41;s:178:"If you click your remote and hear the garage door openers motor running but the door wont open the first thing you should do is check to see that the manual release isnt engaged.";i:42;s:49:"Usually located towards the front of your garage.";i:43;s:29:"Here are three possibilities.";i:44;s:95:"One of the most likely culprits when you have a crooked garage door is a broken torsion spring.";i:45;s:161:"Your garage door has two overhead springs some doors have the springs on the side called extension springs that are responsible for opening and closing the door.";i:46;s:321:"If the garage door is the only way in then you can probably save yourself a lot of heartache by ringing us straight away and requesting an emergency call-out because all automated doors have built-in security locks so if the remote does not open it then that door is not going to open from the outside without assistance.";i:47;s:28:"Do not stand under the door.";i:48;s:45:"Do not attempt this if the door is wide open.";i:49;s:55:"It will come crashing down and could cause some damage.";i:50;s:78:"This is best for when the door wont open or if it close to the ground anyways.";i:51;s:89:"If the door still does not budge the problem may be with the tracks rollers or springers.";i:52;s:77:"Assuming that the overhead garage door track is not bent this will work fine.";i:53;s:121:"The ends of the garage door tracks are usually held in place by metal angles that are attached to the ceiling or rafters.";i:54;s:70:"The metal angles have holes in them some are slotted and some are not.";i:55;s:70:"The idea is to have the track parallel to the door in its up position.";}}